Durban - Two students were arrested when students embarked on protest action at the University of KwaZulu-Natal on Thursday. The students are expected to appear at the Durban Magistrate’s Court on Friday. The university suspended classes citing the student’s violent protests on the Westville, Howard College and Edgewood campus. The students were reportedly protesting over accommodation and issues with the National Student Financial Aid Scheme. Provincial police spokesperson Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane said 80 students embarked in protest. “We can confirm the protest today at Howard College, about 80 students embarked in a protest. They threw stones at the police and security guards. Two students were arrested for public violence. They will appear in the Durban Magistrates’ Court tomorrow. The police are still monitoring,” he said. It was unclear if the university would be reopened on Friday.  UKZN management has suspended academic programmed at Westville and Edgewood until further notice. If the situation worsens, UKZN said they will consider closing the cpus incl residences #UKZNprotest @TheMercurySA pic.twitter.com/WDKEeLZFa7